                    },
                    "company": "Utrecht University",
                    "description": "My dissertation lends insight into how a complex and layered 'global justice assemblage' (as I choose to define it) of transnational actors, with different interests and strategies, cooperated and competed with each other on the pressing issue of how to secure and how to bring justice to the northern Ugandan conflict. It illustrates how an assembly of actors (including the government of Uganda, the ICC, the US, African Union and NGOs) varyingly have upheld a \u2018new war\u2019 frame of the violent conflict between the Lord\u2019s Resistance Army and the government of Uganda. Secondly, it examines how this new war frame legitimised a number of judicial and military interventions, purportedly to \u2018protect the human rights of others'. Thirdly, it reflects on how these interventions played out in the day-to-day lives of those targeted, both discursively and materially. Finally, it analyses who had an interest in upholding these signifying narratives and institutional responses. \n\nMy research has culminated in a number of publications that focus on some of the different types of institutions and interventions that have been implemented to secure and bring justice to the northern Ugandan conflict, such as the International Criminal Court, the International Crimes Division of the Ugandan High Court and the US Africa command's (AFRICOMs) military mission to counter the LRA.",
